EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM [40 CFR 68.155(F)]

The Port Huron WTP Emergency Response Plan for Chlorine Leaks and Spills details the mechanisms that are in place to notify emergency responders when there has been a release of chlorine.  Both the Port Huron Wastewater Treatment Plant (WWTP) and the Port Huron Fire Department may be called to respond to a chlorine incident.

The Port Huron WTP Emergency Response Plan for Chlorine Leaks and Spills also contains the following:
7 A discussion of the hazards associated with chlorine;
7 Operations procedures that minimize the likelihood of an accidental release of chlorine;
7 A list of emergency equipment that is maintained on-site for emergency response and its location;
7 Employee awareness training;
7 Leak detection indicators at the facility;
7 Procedures to follow in an emergency; and
7 A list of phone numbers to be contacted during an accidental release.

PLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY [40 CFR 68.155(G)]

After consideration of the identified release scenarios, the accident history, and a review of the latest PHA for the chlorination system at Port Huron WTP, no changes to the system were deemed necessary by the plant.

The Port Huron WTP plans to eliminate the need for chlorine in the disinfection process by the end of 2001.  At that time, Port Huron WTP will no longer store chlorine on-site and will no longer be subject to the requirements of the RMP Rule.
